How can I make a program that targets specific file types? In C++?
You can use the `boost::filesystem` library to iterate over all files in a directory and check their extension to determine if they match a specific type. Here's an example:
```cpp
#include <boost/filesystem.hpp>
#include <boost/algorithm/string.hpp>

namespace fs = boost::filesystem;

int main() {
    fs::path dir("path/to/directory");
    fs::directory_iterator end;

    for (fs::directory_iterator it(dir); it!= end; ++it) {
        fs::path p = it->path();
        if (fs::is_regular_file(p)) {
            std::string extension = p.string().substr(p.string().find_last_of(".") + 1);
            if (boost::algorithm::iequals(extension, "txt")) {
                // This is a text file, do something with it
            } else if (boost::algorithm::iequals(extension, "pdf")) {
                // This is a PDF file, do something with it
            }
        }
    }

    return 0;
}
```
In this example, we're using the `boost::filesystem` library to iterate over all files in the specified directory.
